{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655556"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:03:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:03:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18675"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18675"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11407"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76797"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11407"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18675"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62296"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10308"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26431"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76797"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA person steps on a sharp object with their right foot. This triggers a withdrawal reflex that involves coordinated muscle activity on both sides of the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the crossed extensor reflex response in this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right leg extension and left leg flexion","Right leg flexion only","Bilateral leg flexion","Right leg flexion and left leg extension","Bilateral leg extension"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eright leg flexion and left leg extension\u003C/strong\u003E response is the correct pattern of muscle activation in the crossed extensor reflex. When the right foot encounters a painful stimulus, interneurons in the spinal cord coordinate:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFlexion of the ipsilateral (right) leg to withdraw from the stimulus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EExtension of the contralateral (left) leg to maintain balance and support body weight\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight leg extension and left leg flexion\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern would cause the person to fall towards the painful stimulus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral leg flexion\u003C/strong\u003E - This would cause the person to collapse\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral leg extension\u003C/strong\u003E - This would prevent withdrawal from the painful stimulus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight leg flexion only\u003C/strong\u003E - Without contralateral extension, the person would lose balance\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis protective reflex involves multiple synapses in the spinal cord and occurs automatically without input from the brain. The interneurons ensure coordinated activation of flexor muscles on the stimulated side and extensor muscles on the opposite side.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The crossed extensor reflex involves ipsilateral flexion and contralateral extension to maintain balance when withdrawing from noxious stimuli.","Interneurons in the spinal cord coordinate the reciprocal activation and inhibition of flexor and extensor muscles on both sides.","This polysynaptic reflex is protective and occurs without conscious control from higher brain centres."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62296"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18675"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62296"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T13:03:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T13:04:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11407"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76797"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"202